{{Infobox person | name = Eugène Lepoittevin | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = Eugène Modeste Edmond Poidevin | birth_date = 31 July 1806 | birth_place = Paris, France | death_date = {{d-da|6 August 1870|31 July 1806|}} | death_place = Paris, France | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | residence = | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | education = | employer = | occupation = Painter | title = | salary = | networth = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse = | children = | parents = | relatives = [[Guy de Maupassant]] <small>(cousin)</small> }} '''Eugène Lepoittevin''' (1806-1870) was a French landscape painter, lithographer and caricaturist. He was appointed as [[Peintre de la Marine]] for the [[Minister of Defence (France)|French Ministry of Defence]] in 1849. His work is exhibited in many museums in France and at the [[Victoria & Albert Museum]] in London.
==Early life== Eugène Lepoittevin was born as Eugène Modeste Edmond Poidevin on 31 July 1806 in Paris, France.<ref name="bnfeugene">{{cite web|title=Eugène Modeste Edmond Poidevin (1806-1870)|url=http://data.bnf.fr/14953612/eugene_modeste_edmond_poidevin/|website=Bibliothèque nationale de France|accessdate=February 27, 2017}}</ref><ref name="vandalepoittevin">{{cite web|title=Rocky Coast near Le Havre: Sunset|url=https://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O132099/rocky-coast-near-le-havre-oil-painting-lepoittevin-eugene-modeste/|website=Victoria & Albert Museum|accessdate=February 27, 2017}}</ref> His cousin was [[Guy de Maupassant]].<ref name="muhlstein144">{{cite book|last1=Muhlstein|first1=Anka|title=The Pen and the Brush: How Passion for Art Shaped Nineteenth-Century French Novels|date=2017|publisher=[[Other Press]]|location=New York City|isbn=9781590518052|oclc=949640008|page=144|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=eHUhDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA144&lpg=PA144&dq=Eug%C3%A8ne+Lepoittevin&source=bl&ots=m0Y6Y1xMoL&sig=tzYikvjENutwIKgp-R00zWaGNfk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjokciXmbHSAhUMK8AKHQjZCNI4HhDoAQgeMAE#v=onepage&q=Eug%C3%A8ne%20Lepoittevin&f=false}}</ref> He was trained as a painter by [[Louis Hersent]] and [[Xavier Leprince]].<ref name="bnfeugene"/><ref name="vandalepoittevin"/>
==Career== [[File:Eugène Lepoittevin - Baignade à Étretat.jpg|thumb|375px|Les bains de mer à Entretat.]] Lepoittevin became a painter, lithographer and caricaturist.<ref name="bnfeugene"/> Some of his drawings were published in ''La Caricature''.<ref name="bnfeugene"/> He did many landscape paintings of [[Étretat]] in [[Normandy]].<ref name="bnfeugene"/> For example, Empress [[Eugénie de Montijo]], the wife of Emperor [[Napoleon III]], acquired his ''Les bains de mer à Entretat''.<ref name="granger211">{{cite book|last1=Granger|first1=Catherine|title=L'empereur et les arts: la liste civile de Napoléon III|date=2005|publisher=Ecole Nationale Des Chartes|location=Paris|isbn=9782900791714|page=211|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=oTESsdmY_ugC&pg=PA211&lpg=PA211&dq=Eug%C3%A8ne+Lepoittevin+ecole+des+beaux-arts&source=bl&ots=0wqjwgzkFG&sig=87AKK9Vfplz_LjHhnaf9Kbho5F4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj8uK-9lrHSAhVHKMAKHXRxCSE4ChDoAQgoMAU#v=onepage&q=Eug%C3%A8ne%20Lepoittevin%20ecole%20des%20beaux-arts&f=false}}</ref>
Lepoittevin exhibited his work at the [[Salon (Paris)|Salon]] in Paris from 1831 onwards.<ref name="vandalepoittevin"/> He was appointed as [[Peintre de la Marine]] in 1849.<ref name="bnfeugene"/>
==Death and legacy== Lepoittevin died on 6 August 1870 in Paris, France.<ref name="bnfeugene"/>
His works are exhibited at the [[Maison de Balzac]] and the [[Hôtel de Brienne]] (home to the [[Minister of Defence (France)|Ministry of Defence]]) in Paris, the [[Palace of Versailles]] and the [[Musée Lambinet]] in [[Versailles]], the [[Château de Dieppe]], the [[Musée de la Faïence et des Beaux-Arts]] in [[Nevers]], the [[Musée des Beaux-Arts de Nantes|Musée des Beaux-Arts]] in [[Nantes]], the [[Musée Magnin]] in [[Dijon]], the [[Musée des beaux-arts de Troyes|Musée des beaux-arts]] in [[Troyes]], the [[Musée des Beaux-Arts de Rouen|Musée des Beaux-Arts]] in [[Rouen]], the [[Musée des beaux-arts de Marseille|Musée des beaux-arts]] in [[Marseille]], the [[Musée des beaux-arts de Chambéry|Musée des beaux-arts]] in [[Chambéry]], the [[Musée Sarret de Grozon]] in [[Arbois]], the [[Musée maritime de l'île Tatihou]] in [[Saint-Vaast-la-Hougue]], the museum in [[Soissons]],<ref name="frenchculture">{{cite web|title=LEPOITTEVIN Eugène|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/joconde_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_98=AUTR&VALUE_98=LEPOITTEVIN%20Eug%E8ne&DOM=All&REL_SPECIFIC=3|website=French Ministry of Culture|accessdate=February 27, 2017}}</ref> and the [[Victoria & Albert Museum]] in London.<ref name="vandalepoittevin"/>
