{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Van Gogh - Interieur eines Restaurants in Arles.jpeg | image_size = | title = Interior of a Restaurant in Arles | artist = [[Vincent van Gogh]] | year = 1888 | catalogue = F549a JH1573 | medium = [[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric = 65.5 | width_metric = 81.0 | metric_unit = cm | city = [[Private collection]] }}
{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Van Gogh - Das Restaurant Carrel in Arles.jpeg | image_size = | title = Interior of the Restaurant Carrel in Arles | artist = [[Vincent van Gogh]] | year = 1888 | catalogue = F549 JH1572 | medium = [[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric = 54.0 | width_metric = 64.5 | metric_unit = cm | city = [[Private collection]] }}
'''''Interior of a Restaurant in Arles''''' is a colored oil painting executed by the Dutch artist [[Vincent van Gogh]] on an industrially primed canvas of size 25 ''(Toile de 25 figure)'' in [[Arles]], France, late August, 1888.
Accurately dating ''Interior of a Restaurant in Arles'' has been difficult, largely because van Gogh never mentioned the painting in any existing letter.<ref>[http://www.vangoghletters.org See www.vangoghletters.org]</ref> Pierre Leprohon placed it in late August, 1888, due in part to the blossoming sunflowers<ref>Leprohon, Pierre, ''Tel fut Van Gogh'', Editions du Sud, 1964, p 415</ref> and this has been generally accepted, including by leading 20th century van Gogh scholar [[Jan Hulsker]].<ref name= "Hulsker 356">Hulsker p. 356</ref> It is one of two studies Vincent created of this restaurant, the other being ''Interior of the Restaurant Carrel in Arles''. Long supposed to be a view from inside the Hotel Carrel, [[Jacob Baart de la Faille | de la Faille]] remarks they were probably the interior of the restaurant next to the [[Yellow House (painting) | Yellow House]]''.<ref>De La Faille p. 232</ref>
==Genesis==
While certainly a representation of diners in Arles (regardless of the cafe), in his article ''Van Gogh's Last Supper: Transforming "the guise of observable reality,"'' <ref>[http://www.arths.org.uk/about/arthsa/issue41 See Art History Supplement, Vol. 4, Issue 1, January, 2014]</ref> Baxter argues this is van Gogh's initial attempt in creating a [[Symbolist]] or [[Boats du Rhône|''sacred realism'']] <ref>See Silverman, Debora, Van Gogh and Gauguin: The Search for Sacred Art, Farrar, Straus and Giroux, 2000</ref> ''[[Last Supper]]'':{{quote|text=There are a number of similarities between this painting and [[Renaissance]] Last Suppers. In the center is a serving figure. Most of the diners are stretched along the far side of the table. Three wine carafes feature prominently in the foreground. Admittedly, not much, but it is a start ...}}
Although Hulsker argued that determining whether this or its sister painting came first would be speculation,<ref group= "Notes">Hulsker did not believe JH1572 was a preliminary sketch for JH1573 and suggested that Vincent made two near identical copies because one was intended for the owner of the cafe.</ref><ref name= "Hulsker 356"/> Baxter offers the following argument: the second version is painted in a [[Cloisonnist]] style, giving it a stained glass window effect, a suitable medium for a ''Last Supper'' painting; and van Gogh has made a number of changes to the final version, most notably: adding bread and placing a new wine bottle before the central serving figure, giving it emphasis. Furthermore, van Gogh added more diners, including the figure hiding behind, what was once a vase of flowers, now appears to be a palm frond. Also, the flower arrangement on the left now resembles the top of a [[Pollaxe|poll axe]] and is at about the same position where [[Simon Peter]] wields a blade in [[Leonardo da Vinci]]'s [[The Last Supper (da Vinci)|version]]. But most importantly, right next to it, van Gogh has replicated Leonardo’s leaning image of the [[apostle John]], van Gogh’s favorite.<ref>See Naifeh & Smith, 2011</ref>
Finally, van Gogh has enframed a female serving figure within vases of flowers, a motif he would return to months later with his ''[[The Roulin Family (Van Gogh series)|Berceuse]]'' triptych.<ref>Van Uitert, Evert, ''Vincent van Gogh and Paul Gauguin in competition: Vincent’s original contribution'', in ''Simiolus: Netherlands Quarterly for the History of Art'', Vol. 11, No. 2 (1980), pp. 81-106</ref> And lastly, all the empty chairs, which can be immediately recognizable from ''[[Vincent van Gogh's Décoration for the Yellow House|Vincent’s Chair]]'', also his ''[[Vincent van Gogh's Décoration for the Yellow House|Bedroom in Arles]]'', and he’d just bought twelve to furnish the [[Yellow House (painting)|Yellow House]] literally hours before beginning his final Symbolist's ''Last Supper'' ''[[Café Terrace at Night]]''<ref>[http://vangoghletters.org/vg/letters/let677/letter.html#n-2 See www.vangoghletters.org Letter 677, note 2]</ref>
